comment_data.body:
I think the important distinction is between three separate policies:

- process topology: whether Nvim creates a separate process group/session for the child;
- kill policy: whether `SystemObj:kill()` targets only the spawned process or the whole group/tree;
- ownership: whether Nvim stops the process during teardown.

#39562 bundles topology and kill policy together for all Unix `vim.system()` calls. That changes the default shape of processes started by `vim.system()`, and makes `SystemObj:kill()` mean "kill the process group" rather than "signal the spawned process".

That default topology change can also break callers that run Nvim as part of a supervised process group. If a supervisor cancels Nvim's process group, children that `vim.system()` moved into a separate session/process group may no longer receive that cancellation. `jobstart()` can use this topology because it also has teardown ownership: non-detached jobs are stopped by Nvim when Nvim exits. `vim.system()` does not currently have that ownership path, so copying only the topology/kill part is much riskier.

I think tree/job-control semantics should be explicit and backwards compatible. One way to do that is to introduce a `mode` option which describes the lifecycle contract:

```lua
vim.system(cmd)                         -- mode = 'process'
vim.system(cmd, { mode = 'process' })   -- current behavior
vim.system(cmd, { mode = 'job' })       -- owned job-control
vim.system(cmd, { mode = 'detached' })  -- detached job-control
```

Proposed semantics:

- `mode = 'process'`:
  - default;
  - current `vim.system()` behavior;
  - no forced new process group/session;
  - `SystemObj:kill()` signals only the spawned process;
  - Nvim does not own process-tree cleanup on exit.
- `mode = 'job'`:
  - `jobstart()`-style owned job;
  - internally, Unix can still use `UV_PROCESS_DETACHED`/`setsid()` so the child gets its own process group;
  - `SystemObj:kill()` stops the process group/tree;
  - Nvim stops the job during teardown.
- `mode = 'detached'`:
  - `SystemObj:kill()` stops the process group/tree;
  - Nvim does not stop it automatically when Nvim exits.

The existing `detach` option can be deprecated in favor of `mode=detached`. Mixing `mode` and `detach` should be rejected.

This keeps existing `vim.system()` callers compatible and gives users an explicit way to request `jobstart()`-style semantics.
